  "prompt": "What are the best anime movies?",
  "response": "Determining the \"best\" anime movies can be subjective, as it often depends on individual taste and preferences. However, some anime movies are widely acclaimed and have gained significant popularity and critical recognition over the years. Here are some of the most highly regarded anime movies:\n\n1. **Spirited Away (2001)** - Directed by Hayao Miyazaki and produced by Studio Ghibli, this film is often considered one of the greatest animated films ever made. It won the Academy Award for Best Animated Feature in 2003.\n\n2. **Akira (1988)** - Directed by Katsuhiro Otomo, this cyberpunk classic is known for its groundbreaking animation and complex narrative. It has had a significant influence on both anime and global pop culture.\n\n3. **Your Name (2016)** - Directed by Makoto Shinkai, this romantic fantasy drama became a global sensation and is praised for its beautiful animation and emotional story.\n\n4. **Princess Mononoke (1997)** - Another masterpiece by Hayao Miyazaki, this epic fantasy film tackles themes of environmentalism and human conflict.\n\n5. **Grave of the Fireflies (1988)** - Directed by Isao Takahata, this heartbreaking war drama is a poignant and powerful film about the struggles of two siblings during World War II.\n\n6. **My Neighbor Totoro (1988)** - Directed by Hayao Miyazaki, this charming and whimsical film about two young sisters and their adventures with magical forest creatures has become a beloved classic.\n\n7. **Ghost in the Shell (1995)** - Directed by Mamoru Oshii, this influential sci-fi film explores themes of identity, consciousness, and technology. It has inspired many other works in the genre.\n\n8. **The Wind Rises (2013)** - Directed by Hayao Miyazaki, this biographical film tells the story of Jiro Horikoshi, the designer of Japanese fighter planes during World War II. It's a beautifully crafted and emotionally resonant film.\n\n9. **Perfect Blue (1997)** - Directed by Satoshi Kon, this psychological thriller delves into the dark side of fame and identity, offering a complex and gripping narrative.\n\n10. **A Silent Voice (2016)** - Directed by Naoko Yamada, this film deals with themes of bullying, redemption, and the struggles of communication, offering a heartfelt and emotional story.\n\nThese films represent a range of genres and styles within anime, showcasing the diversity and creativity of the medium.",
